The new anti-globalization reaction
PRINCETON – A palpable sense of unease was evident at the last G-7 summit in Ise-Shima, Japan.
At the next meeting of the world's major developed economies' leaders, no one can say which of them will be part of the populist insurgents.
President Donald Trump could represent the United States, or President Marine Le Pen could represent France.
They could sit with British Prime Minister Boris Johnson, Italian Prime Minister Beppe Grillo, or even with German Chancellor Frauke Petry.
Each of them could become a champion of nationalism and isolationism, in one form or another.
The reaction against globalization has been ongoing for two decades.
At the end of the 20th century, the global trend apparently was toward convergence, and people seemed to be consuming the same products everywhere.
McDonald's has exemplified this kind of globalization: breaking into the stores of this chain has become a standard form of protest against globalization.
But in recent times, the nature of globalization has changed, as has the reaction against it.
Although the world is becoming increasingly interconnected, there is a feeling that we understand foreigners less.
In response to the evolution of consumer preferences (which are increasingly more specific), companies are relocating their production closer to the markets where the goods will be sold.
This weakens the growth of international trade.
Such an "on-shore" anchoring is not new.
In the 1970s and 1980s, Americans feared that the United States would be flooded by Japanese cars. They then began to produce these cars domestically.
Currently, most "Japanese" automobiles sold in the United States are manufactured in the United States. However, reversing the globalization of goods is now easier than ever, thanks to advances in robotic engineering and the development of processes such as 3D printing.
Thus, the current critique of globalization tends to focus less on commercial issues.
But this evolution reflects not only the slowdown in trade growth.
Consumers in wealthy countries are much more comfortable with foreign products; in some cases, they are even dependent on them, from constantly updated electronics to the low-cost, "ephemeral fashion" that has become predominant in advanced economies.
Instead of rejecting foreign products, today's opponents of globalization reject foreigners.
Disputes over investor protection clauses in trade agreements such as the Trans-Pacific Partnership or the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership focus on issues of obscure courts protecting the interests of foreign companies and allegedly undermining national sovereignty.
Next comes the global refugee crisis: in Europe, in particular, the anxiety surrounding this influx may be a precursor to a broader rejection of immigration from bankrupt and impoverished countries.
Why are the populations of advanced countries so afraid of foreigners?
It's not as if they had never been exposed to other cultures.
Many citizens of these countries travel constantly to distant destinations, and hundreds of millions of people worldwide head each year toward advanced countries.
The problem lies in the way we travel.
Today, we are more inclined to experience things quickly and superficially, rather than immersing ourselves in a culture.
But as modern game theory teaches us, a single interaction is very different from continuous contact.
If participants are aware that they have a unique and limited experience, they have no interest in building a deeper foundation of understanding or cooperation.
Continuous exchange is necessary to build trust.
The result of the superficial approach of current tourism is evident for any major tourist destination.
Restaurants are unlikely to provide good or even honest service to people who surely will never come back.
Restaurants serve mediocre (or worse) food without a smile, taxi drivers cheat you, and hoteliers lie about their amenities.
Furthermore, this small game may experience interruptions.
In places where tourism has become a source of foreign revenue, it also becomes an attractive target for terrorists who base their ideology on anti-Western resentment.
A few attacks in places like Bali or the Red Sea tourist complexes are enough to cause deep economic destabilization.
Tourism companies respond to such risks by minimizing contact with the local population.
The emblem of modern tourism is a gigantic cruise ship, where passengers can spend a few hours at each destination (to visit a magnificent Caribbean island or an ancient Mediterranean port), but always sleep in the same bed.
The new Royal Caribbean ship Harmony of the Seas aims to recreate all the world's climates.
Indeed, this ship, over 30 meters long and as tall as the Eiffel Tower, contains a tropical park and an ice rink (in addition to its 23 pools and 42 bars).
Tourist bus or train companies do the same to ensure the safety of their clients, releasing them only for a limited time at a famous site—just long enough to take a few photos.
This style of travel places a strain on the capacity of local infrastructure.
There is often not enough space to walk along the canals of Venice or on the path leading to the Acropolis.
This approach reinforces mutual misunderstanding.
Visitors stay within the limits of their pre-planned excursions, encountering only swindlers who offer them cheap trinkets or overpriced taxi rides.
Native people don't particularly appreciate tourist groups gathering around their most beautiful sites.
No one feels particularly involved, nor do they maintain any relationship of trust.
It is easy to feel a certain nostalgia for that era when tourism involved long stays and extended encounters with very different cultures.
It would obviously be impossible, for the current number of visitors, to spend weeks or even months entirely in old monasteries.
But it is possible to imagine certain scenarios in which visitors and their hosts could interact in a more personal way.
For example, Airbnb can provide a much more appealing experience than a hotel, or worse, than a cruise ship.
Is there a policy equivalent to Airbnb?
Could world leaders participate in summits like the G-7 by living and working for an extended period of time in a foreign country?
Not long after the United States entered World War II, Winston Churchill made this famous gesture of lifting camp to stay at the White House for 24 days, in order to strengthen the transatlantic alliance of Britain by deepening his relationship with Franklin Roosevelt.
This level of familiarity could well be the greatest enemy of today's anti-globalist populists.
